properties.name: West Sayan Fault
properties.notes: very rough interpreted segment in between more evident segments.
Some OK quaternary scarps in landsat/google earth
Strange but well-defined scarp w/ some imagery evidence for quaternary offsets. May have a significant component of strike-slip, kinematics currently unknown.

This is the northern part of a long (~100 km) N-S fault ; a few moderate earthquakes (6.7, 6.6) in 2011-2012 probably reactivated the northern end and are dextral and reverse-dextral.  Additional information is unknown but I haven't searched in depth.
Southern part of a ~100 km long N-S fault. Focal mechs and to some degree fault geomorphology suggest toe north is dextral-reverse, but this segemnt  looks dextral-normal (triangular facets  etc.
Amazing sinistral bedrock offsets

properties.name: Azas-Sentsa Fault
properties.notes: Western half has excellent rupture visible in SRTM, for km after km. When the fault gets into the mountains and is in a long glacial valley, this fades but the linearity of the valley makes it obvious where the fault is.

properties.name: Central Sayan Fault
properties.notes: Clear bedrock fault, but Quaternary activity is uncertain. In many cases it looks like geomorphic features are cut but obvious offsets with consisten kinematics are lacking.  However, imagery is not great, so this relies only on SRTM.
Could have a sinistral component

Sinistral(?) section in between two inferred sinistral-oblique segments. Inferred to be more SS because of the lack of relief across the fault.

properties.name: Upper Pil'tun North
properties.notes: Rupture trace of the 1995 Neftegorsk (Ms 7.6) earthquake. Trace is very unclear in the central and northern part, so the wrong scarps may be mapped. However, the trace is here somewhere.

Best candidate for Siberian-Okhostk plate boundary at this latitude. Khozurin infers dextral slip.
some structure here, who knows how old
Interpreted as an east-dipping reverse fault, given the general plate kinematics at this part of the globe. However, it could be an inactive west-dipping normal fault.
Long lineament in imagery, google earth. Some seismicity in region, minor velocity gradient.
Old fault / lineament. Some regional seismicity, velocity gradient.
